Package: mediawiki-dom-snapshot
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 python3-bs4,
 python3-lxml,
 python3-pil,
 python3-imagehash,
 python3-playwright
Recommends: chromium
Description: Headless DOM + asset + screenshot snapshotter for MediaWiki regression testing
 Drives a headless Chromium against a running MediaWiki instance via
 Playwright, captures per page the post-JS DOM, a viewport screenshot,
 and every external asset body indexed by sha256, then offers a
 three-axis diff (HTML text, asset content, screenshot pixel +
 perceptual-hash distance) so a refactor can be proven not to have
 changed anything visually or behaviourally.
 .
 Use case: detect HTML/CSS/JS/image changes introduced by MediaWiki
 core / extension upgrades or by site-CSS refactors. Capture a
 baseline before the change, run again after, run the diff.
 .
 Ships the page list under /etc/mediawiki-dom-snapshot/pages.conf. The
 baseline corpus and capture output are large, regenerable runtime data
 kept in the operator's private cache, not in the package.

Package: sdwdate-gui-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 python3-pyqt5,
 sdwdate-gui
Suggests: xvfb,
 stalonetray,
 xdotool,
 x11-utils,
 weston,
 qtwayland5,
 dbus,
 python3-dbus,
 python3-gi,
 python3-coverage
Description: Regression tests and fuzzer for the sdwdate-gui applet
 Headless test suite for sdwdate-gui-server. Drives the real
 SdwdateTrayIcon and SdwdateGuiClient classes under the Qt offscreen
 platform plugin, so most of it needs neither an X server, a system
 tray, nor a live qrexec connection.
 .
 Unit coverage ('sdwdate-gui-tests' command): the client de-duplication
 invariant that keeps a Qubes VM from being listed more than once in the
 tray menu when it reconnects (Qubes authenticated-qrexec-name and
 non-Qubes self-reported-name branches), tray menu activation (left- and
 right-click open the menu; the Wayland opt-out), and wire-protocol
 regressions (a fragmented message must not hang the parser, a newline in
 a status message must not get the client kicked), and tray-deferral
 invariants (the tray icon waits for a system tray host so Qt binds
 StatusNotifier rather than the XEmbed fallback, while the IPC socket comes
 up immediately and pre-tray clients are buffered and replayed).
 .
 Fuzzer ('sdwdate-gui-tests-fuzz' command): a simulator that drives the
 server over a real local socket with a directed corpus plus random and
 mutated byte streams and random client-lifecycle sequences, for both the
 Qubes and non-Qubes paths. It checks for hangs, crashes, duplicate
 names, failed registration / de-registration, and stuck menus, and (with
 python3-coverage) reports line coverage of the server. The RNG seed is
 printed so any finding is reproducible.
 .
 Integration coverage ('sdwdate-gui-tests-integration' command): the same
 tray menu driven end to end on a real display -- a headless Xvfb with an
 XEmbed systray host for genuine left- and right-click delivery, a
 headless Wayland compositor for the Wayland opt-out, and a late-started
 StatusNotifierWatcher on a private session bus that guards against the
 tray-icon startup race (deferred construction so Qt picks the
 StatusNotifier backend rather than falling back to XEmbed). These need
 the tooling in Suggests (xvfb, stalonetray, xdotool, x11-utils, weston,
 qtwayland5, dbus, python3-dbus, python3-gi); any phase whose tooling is
 absent is skipped, not failed.
 .
 All commands require the 'sdwdate-gui' package, as the tests import its
 server module.

Package: privleap-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 privleap,
 sudo
Suggests: python3-coverage,
 python3-pytest,
 python3-hypothesis
Description: Security regression tests and fuzzers for the privleap privilege manager
 In-process security suite ('privleap-tests' command, no root): drives the
 REAL privleap code over exactly the surface an unprivileged local user can
 reach through their comm socket -- the place a bug could become arbitrary
 code execution as root.
 .
 The wire-protocol parser fuzzer wraps a server-side privleap session around a
 socketpair and feeds it a directed corpus plus random, structured, and
 mutational byte streams, asserting that every input is either parsed into a
 message type legal for that socket (with re-validated fields) or cleanly
 rejected -- never a crash, a hang (watchdog-guarded), or a type confusion --
 and that all valid traffic round-trips. The authorization-engine property
 test builds actions from the real account database and checks authorize_user
 against an independent reference model over thousands of randomized
 action/caller pairs, with the explicit invariant that a non-root caller is
 never authorized without a matching user or group rule, plus oracle-hardening
 (an unknown action and a forbidden one are indistinguishable). When
 python3-pytest and python3-hypothesis are present it also runs Hypothesis
 property tests of the pure parser helpers (argument-count codec round-trip,
 validate_id charset/length invariants).
 .
 Randomized fuzzer ('privleap-tests-fuzz' command, no root): the same parser
 fuzzer with a random seed and, when python3-coverage is present, a coverage
 report of the privleap library. The seed is printed so any finding is
 reproducible.
 .
 Coverage-guided fuzzer ('privleap-tests-fuzz-atheris' command, no root): an
 Atheris (libFuzzer) harness that drives the same server-side parser but
 mutates inputs guided by the coverage it observes inside the privleap library,
 reaching deep parser branches a blind generator rarely hits. It follows the
 ecosystem's fuzz_<pkg>.py convention and is ClusterFuzzLite-ready. Atheris is
 not packaged in Debian; install it with 'pip install atheris'. Without it the
 harness skips.
 .
 Stateful session fuzzer ('privleap-tests-session-fuzz' command, needs sudo):
 fuzzes the live daemon's multi-message session state machine and threading,
 not just single-frame parsing -- random and directed message sequences (out of
 order, split, interleaved) from many concurrent connections -- asserting the
 daemon never crashes or wedges and that an unauthorized action is never
 executed regardless of ordering. Runs a throwaway privleapd inside a private
 mount namespace, so the host's privleapd is untouched.
 .
 Live-daemon end-to-end test ('privleap-tests-e2e' command, needs sudo): runs
 the real privleapd and a real comm-socket client inside a private mount
 namespace (fresh tmpfs over /run and /etc/privleap, so the host's privleapd,
 state, and config are never touched and cleanup is automatic), proving end to
 end that an unauthorized action is never executed, an authorized one is, a
 malformed-frame barrage neither crashes nor corrupts the daemon's
 authorization, and an environment-injection attempt planted in the calling
 user's ~/.pam_environment and /etc/environment (LD_PRELOAD, BASH_ENV, marker
 variables) never reaches a root action.
 .
 Production-faithful variant ('privleap-tests-e2e-systemd' command, needs
 sudo): the same security phases against the REAL privleapd.service driven by
 systemd, so the daemon comes up exactly as in production (Type=notify
 handshake, watchdog, the genuine service environment and unit sandboxing) and
 actions run with the real systemd env. It mutates the live service (stop, swap
 config, start) and restores it on exit via atexit and signal handlers; the
 environment-injection check uses the real ~/.pam_environment and
 /etc/environment, backed up and restored.
 .
 The tests target the installed privleap by default; set PRIVLEAP_REPO to run
 them against a derivative-maker checkout instead.

Package: onion-grater-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 python3-yaml,
 python3-stem,
 python3-psutil,
 onion-grater
Suggests: tor,
 bitcoind
Description: Regression and reproduction tests for the onion-grater control-port filter
 In-process unit / reproduction suite ('onion-grater-tests' command): imports
 the real onion-grater filtering code and replays each application's Tor
 control command sequence, asserting legitimate commands are allowed and
 argument-injection variants are blocked. It also reproduces the fixed Bisq
 SETCONF deanonymization (a control-port argument-injection vulnerability) and
 the follow-up DEL_ONION / HSFETCH / onion_client_auth_add / AUTHCHALLENGE
 hardening, old-vs-new, through the same matcher. No root, no network, no real
 Tor; validated non-vacuous against the pre-fix tree.
 .
 Full-stack end-to-end ('onion-grater-tests-e2e' command): a throwaway offline
 tor plus the real onion-grater binary plus a control client over the veth
 network, proving the deanonymization vector reaches Tor on the old profile and
 is blocked (510) on the new one. Needs tor and sudo (only the privileged
 setup steps are sudo'd, and they are cleaned up).
 .
 Also under /usr/share/onion-grater-tests: a real-application driver
 (bitcoind_drive.py, which drives real bitcoind through the filter) and
 adversarial security probes (probe_bypass.py, probe_rewrite.py, verify_dos.py)
 that fuzz the filter for protocol bypasses and the partial-line busy-loop DoS.
 These need sudo and tor; see the README.
 .
 The tests target the installed onion-grater by default; set ONION_GRATER_REPO
 to run them against a derivative-maker checkout instead.

Package: dm-help-steps-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 bash (>= 4),
 python3,
 procps,
 safe-rm
Description: Functional tests for derivative-maker help-steps scripts
 Tests for the helper scripts under derivative-maker help-steps/, currently
 the /proc-based process reaper umount_kill.sh. One victim per detection
 channel (cwd, open fd, mmap-only, exe image, chrooted process) must be
 terminated, SIGTERM-ignoring victims must fall through to the SIGKILL
 escalation, and bystanders (unrelated processes, a sibling tree whose name
 is a string-prefix collision of the target) must survive. Requires root;
 as an unprivileged user every test SKIPs. Run inside a throwaway container
 or sandbox VM.
 .
 The tests target ~/derivative-maker by default; set UMOUNT_KILL_SH to run
 them against another checkout.

Package: genmkfile-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 bash (>= 4),
 genmkfile,
 dctrl-tools,
 dpkg-dev,
 git,
 safe-rm
Description: Regression tests for the genmkfile build-helper target dispatch
 Drives the real genmkfile against a throwaway minimal Debian source package
 and asserts that the deb-cleanup and reprepro-remove / reprepro-add targets
 are routed through genmkfile's full variable setup (make_get_variables), not
 the cheap dependencies-only path reserved for deb-build-dep / deb-run-dep /
 deb-all-dep. This guards the fix for a dispatch mis-classification that
 aborted those targets with 'make_upstream_tarball_relative_path: unbound
 variable' (and the equivalent make_main_changes_file / make_package_list
 failures for the reprepro targets).
 .
 A second check covers the make_use_git_describe_for_version path: a repo
 that sets that flag but also ships debian/control (live-build) must still
 get its deb path variables set (deb-cleanup must not abort with an unbound
 variable) while keeping its git tag version from git describe (commit_<sha>),
 not the changelog version.
 .
 The 'genmkfile-tests' command needs no root, no network and no real reprepro
 (a stub wrapper stands in). It targets genmkfile from PATH by default; set
 GENMKFILE_BIN to test a specific genmkfile, or it falls back to a
 derivative-maker checkout under ~/derivative-maker.

Package: open-link-confirmation-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 python3-pyqt5,
 bash (>= 4),
 sed,
 grep,
 helper-scripts,
 open-link-confirmation
Description: Security and unit tests for the open-link-confirmation link/file dialog
 open-link-confirmation is the $BROWSER / x-www-browser handler: it receives a
 URL or file path from a potentially untrusted source and shows a confirmation
 dialog before opening it. The argument is displayed by piping it through
 helper-scripts' sanitize-string and rendering the result as HTML in a PyQt5
 QTextBrowser. The 'open-link-confirmation-tests' command exercises that whole
 pipeline. No root, no network, no real browser; Qt runs offscreen.
 .
 Sanitization contract: drives the real sanitize-string over a hostile battery
 (Unicode, RTL override, zero-width, ANSI/SGR, OSC-8 hyperlinks, C0/C1/DEL
 control bytes, oversized inputs, markup) and asserts the output stays
 display-safe (ASCII only, length-capped, no control or escape bytes other than
 newline and tab).
 .
 Qt rich-text differential: embeds the sanitized output in the script's exact
 HTML wrapper and parses it with the real Qt engine, asserting the argument
 introduces no clickable anchor or image. This encodes a known parser
 differential (a '<' followed by whitespace then a tag name survives
 sanitize-string's Python parser but Qt reconstructs the tag) as strict-xfail
 regression cases that flip to a hard failure once the bypass is fixed.
 .
 Static audit asserts every displayed message uses only the sanitized argument,
 never the raw argument; a bash unit test asserts source_config()'s
 env-over-config precedence. The tests target the installed
 open-link-confirmation and sanitize-string by default; set
 OPEN_LINK_CONFIRMATION_BIN and SANITIZE_STRING_BIN to test a checkout.

Package: sanitize-string-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 python3-pyqt5,
 bash (>= 4),
 helper-scripts
Description: Deep test and fuzzer for the helper-scripts sanitize family
 The sanitize family (stdisplay, strip_markup, sanitize-string) makes untrusted
 strings safe to display. Its output is embedded, unescaped, into text shown to
 the user both on a terminal and as HTML in msgcollector's PyQt5 QTextBrowser
 dialogs, so it must be safe in both renderers. This suite proves it is, with no
 bypasses, over a curated adversarial corpus and a biased fuzzer. No root, no
 network; Qt runs offscreen and is skipped if PyQt5 is absent.
 .
 It adds the dimension helper-scripts' own property tests cannot: a cross-parser
 differential. helper-scripts checks properties against Python's html.parser;
 the dialog renders with Qt's more lenient parser. A '<' followed by whitespace
 then a tag name, or a '<' produced by entity decoding, is inert to Python but
 Qt revives it into a clickable anchor or image. The suite drives the real Qt
 engine and asserts no anchor / no image / no surviving '<'.
 .
 'sanitize-string-tests' runs the corpus plus a default fuzz sweep;
 'sanitize-string-tests-fuzz' runs a heavy sweep. A minimal QTextBrowser
 reproduction is shipped as qtextbrowser_repro.py. The suite targets the
 installed sanitize-string by default; set SANITIZE_STRING_BIN to test a
 checkout or a not-yet-installed fix.

Package: stcat-family-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 helper-scripts
Description: Comprehensive test and fuzzer for the stcat family of safe-terminal tools
 The stcat family (stcat, stcatn, stecho, stprint, stsponge, sttee, from
 helper-scripts' stdisplay package) makes untrusted text safe to print to a
 terminal. Each tool routes input through stdisplay() and forces its stdout
 (and file outputs) to ASCII. This suite proves, across all six tools, that
 nothing dangerous reaches the terminal. No root, no network.
 .
 In no-colour mode the output is pure printable ASCII plus newline/tab -- no
 Unicode (RLO, zero-width, homoglyphs, C1, line/paragraph separators), no
 control characters, no escape sequences -- over a hostile corpus and a
 byte-level fuzzer. In colour mode Unicode is still stripped and only
 well-formed SGR colour escapes survive; OSC-8 hyperlinks and CSI cursor/clear
 are neutralised. It also checks each tool still performs its function
 (cat / numbered-cat-with-trim / echo / print / sponge / tee) on benign input,
 including file paths, whose written content is verified sanitised.
 .
 'stcat-family-tests' runs the corpus, colour, semantics, and a default fuzz
 sweep; 'stcat-family-tests-fuzz' runs a heavy sweep. The suite targets the
 installed tools by default; set STDISPLAY_REPO to a helper-scripts checkout
 to test that instead.

Package: stdisplay-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 helper-scripts
Description: Comprehensive function-level test and fuzzer for stdisplay()
 stdisplay() (from helper-scripts' stdisplay package) sanitizes untrusted text
 to be safe to print to a terminal; it is the security core the whole stcat
 family routes its input through. Where stcat-family-tests drives the six CLIs
 and only exercises stdisplay() at two colour settings, this suite tests the
 function directly across EVERY colour depth (3/4/8/24-bit), which is the
 bug-prone part: get_sgr_pattern() builds a graded allow-list regex whose
 behaviour changes at every depth. No root, no network.
 .
 It proves each SGR bit-mode (3-bit foreground/background/reset, 4-bit bright,
 8-bit indexed with both ';' and ':' separators, 24-bit truecolor) survives
 verbatim exactly when its depth is enabled and is redacted otherwise; that a
 corpus of dangerous non-SGR escapes (screen clear, cursor movement, the
 device-status/attribute REPORT that injects input, OSC title, OSC-8 hyperlink,
 DCS/APC/PM, RIS reset, charset selection), single-byte C1 controls, C0
 controls / NUL / DEL, and non-ASCII (bidi Trojan-Source, zero-width, BOM, a
 homoglyph, line/paragraph separators) is neutralised at every depth including
 truecolor; that exclude_sgr removes only the code it names; the get_sgr_support()
 NO_COLOR / COLORTERM / fail-closed-TERM logic; idempotence; and the module's own
 docstring examples as exact-string regression pins.
 .
 Every output is checked against an independent, palette-agnostic terminal-safety
 oracle: strip every loose "ESC [ ... m" (SGR, which can only set colour) and
 nothing dangerous may remain -- no leaked escape, no non-printable character. A
 fuzz phase feeds random Unicode, an escape-biased smuggling channel that keeps
 trying to slip a dangerous escape past the allow-list, and random exclude lists,
 asserting the oracle and idempotence hold and the function never raises.
 .
 'stdisplay-tests' runs the pins, benign, graded, redaction, exclude, env,
 idempotence, and a default fuzz sweep; 'stdisplay-tests-fuzz' runs a heavy
 sweep. The suite targets the installed stdisplay package by default; set
 STDISPLAY_REPO to a helper-scripts checkout to test that instead.

Package: unicode-show-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 helper-scripts
Description: Comprehensive test and fuzzer for the unicode-show suspicious-Unicode scanner
 unicode-show (from helper-scripts' unicode_show package) is the mirror image of
 the stcat family: instead of sanitizing untrusted text for a terminal, it
 DETECTS and reports non-ASCII / suspicious Unicode in text or files, exiting 0
 when clean, 1 when a suspicious character is found, and 2 on error (invalid
 UTF-8 or an unreadable file). Decoding is strict, so a non-UTF-8 byte fails
 closed rather than being silently mangled. This suite proves the whole contract
 end to end against the real CLI. No root, no network.
 .
 It drives a hostile corpus (the bidi Trojan-Source control set, zero-width
 characters, BOM, a Cyrillic homoglyph, a combining mark, C1 controls,
 line/paragraph separators, CJK, an emoji, and the C0 control bytes including
 NUL and DEL) and asserts the tool exits 1 and names the exact codepoint (e.g.
 U+202E) it found. Crucially it asserts unicode-show's OWN stdout never leaks the
 raw suspicious bytes it is reporting: over the whole corpus and a byte-level
 fuzzer, the output stays pure printable ASCII plus newline/tab (the tool relies
 on ascii() for this; a regression to repr() would let a printable non-ASCII
 character slip into the terminal, and the suite catches it).
 .
 It also covers the benign path (clean ASCII exits 0 with no output, so detection
 is non-vacuous), the newline / trailing-whitespace / empty-input semantics
 including the UNICODE_SHOW_ALLOW_MISSING_FINAL_NEWLINE suppression, fail-closed
 behaviour on invalid UTF-8 (exit 2 with no byte slipped to stdout) and
 unreadable paths, file-argument scanning, and a hostile filename that must be
 sanitized in the output. A fuzz phase feeds random byte streams and random valid
 Unicode and asserts the tool never crashes, hangs, or breaks the ASCII-output
 invariant.
 .
 'unicode-show-tests' runs the corpus, semantics, fail-closed, and a default
 fuzz sweep; 'unicode-show-tests-fuzz' runs a heavy sweep. The suite targets the
 installed unicode-show by default; set UNICODE_SHOW_REPO to a helper-scripts
 checkout to test that instead.

Package: grep-find-unicode-wrapper-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 grep,
 helper-scripts
Description: Comprehensive test and fuzzer for grep-find-unicode-wrapper
 grep-find-unicode-wrapper (from helper-scripts) is a bash wrapper around grep
 that scans files for suspicious content and lists the files that contain any:
 non-ASCII bytes, the bidi Trojan-Source control set (RHSB-2021-007), and ASCII
 control bytes (C0 minus tab/newline, plus DEL and NUL). It is grep-like -- exit
 0 if a match was found, 1 if not, and it fails loud on a grep error -- and it
 routes the matching file names through stecho so a filename that itself contains
 Unicode cannot smuggle anything to the terminal. This suite proves the whole
 contract end to end against the real wrapper. No root, no network.
 .
 It drives a hostile corpus (bidi controls, zero-width, BOM, a Cyrillic
 homoglyph, a combining mark, C1 controls, CJK, an emoji, an accented letter, and
 the C0 control bytes including NUL and DEL) and asserts each file is detected and
 listed, with a dedicated check that a pure-ASCII control byte -- which the
 non-ASCII greps cannot see -- is still caught by the control-byte grep. It
 asserts a clean file is not flagged (including that trailing whitespace, unlike
 in unicode-show, is NOT a match), that given several files only the dirty ones
 are listed sorted and de-duplicated, that a filename containing suspicious
 Unicode is sanitized in the output (stdout stays pure ASCII), and that a
 nonexistent path fails loud rather than silently reporting no match.
 .
 It also pins the tool's documented stdin limitation: only the first of the four
 greps consumes piped bytes, so a control-only stdin input is a false negative.
 That is encoded as a strict known-limitation assertion which flips to a hard
 failure if stdin handling is ever fixed, prompting a test update. A fuzz phase
 writes random byte files and checks the wrapper's match/no-match exit against an
 independent byte-level oracle, asserting exact agreement and pure-ASCII output.
 .
 'grep-find-unicode-wrapper-tests' runs the corpus, semantics, and a default fuzz
 sweep; 'grep-find-unicode-wrapper-tests-fuzz' runs a heavy sweep. The suite
 targets the installed wrapper by default; set GREP_FIND_UNICODE_WRAPPER_REPO to
 a helper-scripts checkout to test that instead.

Package: check-ref-commits-for-unicode-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 git,
 helper-scripts
Description: Comprehensive test and fuzzer for check-ref-commits-for-unicode
 check-ref-commits-for-unicode (from helper-scripts) is a git-ref guard that
 scans every commit a ref introduces (git log HEAD..<ref>) for suspicious
 Unicode and fails if any is found. For each new commit it runs git show and
 pipes the result through unicode-show, so it scans not just the diff but the
 commit message and the author / committer name and email -- the places a
 Trojan-Source style attack can hide that a plain content scan misses. This
 suite builds throwaway git repos and proves the whole contract end to end
 against the real tool. No root, no network; git is run hermetically.
 .
 It asserts detection of a hostile codepoint hidden in each scanned location
 (file content, commit message, author name, author email, committer name,
 committer email), that the tool names the offending commit, and that its own
 output stays pure ASCII while reporting (unicode-show renders findings as
 [U+XXXX], so nothing raw reaches the terminal). It pins the design choices that
 matter: --unified=0 (no false positive from empty context lines), --no-ext-diff
 and --no-textconv (no external driver or filter hiding the bytes), and the
 identity fields being included in the scan.
 .
 It also covers the benign path (a clean ref, including blank lines and a clean
 merge commit, exits 0 -- so detection is non-vacuous), multi-commit isolation
 (the dirty commit is flagged by sha while clean ones are logged clean), and the
 usage / setup errors, each of which fails loud with its own message (no ref
 given, a nonexistent ref, a ref with no new commits, and a cwd that is not a git
 work tree). The improved tool uses a split exit code -- 0 clean, 1 suspicious
 found, 2 error -- so a caller can tell a real detection from a usage error; the
 suite feature-detects the build's error code and, on a stale build that still
 overloads exit 1, skips only the codes-are-distinct assertion. A fuzz phase
 builds random commits whose payload is clean or carries a suspicious character
 in a random location and checks the verdict against an independent oracle,
 asserting exact agreement and pure-ASCII output.
 .
 'check-ref-commits-for-unicode-tests' runs the corpus, semantics, and a default
 fuzz sweep; 'check-ref-commits-for-unicode-tests-fuzz' runs a heavy sweep. Each
 iteration builds a real commit, so it is heavier per iteration than the
 byte-level sibling suites. The suite targets the installed tool by default; set
 CHECK_REF_COMMITS_REPO to a helper-scripts checkout to test that instead.

Package: git-meld-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 bash (>= 4),
 git,
 developer-meta-files
Description: Adversarial + fuzz hidden-change tests for the git-meld diff driver
 Exercises developer-meta-files' 'git-meld' external diff driver against crafted
 changes on throwaway repos (safe payloads, no network) and asserts its core
 security property: a real change is NEVER rendered as empty/misleading output
 (a change the reviewer cannot see is one an attacker can hide).
 .
 'git-meld-tests' runs two adversarial suites: (1) direct-invocation
 submodule-gitlink cases (commits present, and old/new/both unfetched) that must
 surface the gitlink transition or fail loud; (2) a real-'git diff' suite
 covering mode-only changes (+x), symlink swaps, a regular file whose content
 spoofs a 'Subproject commit' gitlink, Trojan-Source bidi/invisible Unicode, and
 files git skips entirely (marked binary/-diff by .gitattributes) which must
 still appear in the 'git meld' re-dispatch pre-flight. Set GIT_MELD_OLD_REF to
 also demonstrate the pre-hardening code hiding changes.
 .
 'git-meld-tests-fuzz' generates many random commits (random change types +
 adversarial blob contents: NUL/binary, bidi, gitlink-mimic, BOM, long lines)
 and asserts every path git reports as changed appears in what a reviewer sees.
 Deterministic given a seed. Both commands need no root or network.

Package: dm-virtualbox-wiki-links-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 bash (>= 4),
 helper-scripts,
 developer-meta-files
Description: Regression tests for dm-virtualbox-update-local-and-wiki-links
 Reproduces the root cause of three fixed bugs in developer-meta-files'
 'dm-virtualbox-update-local-and-wiki-links' and asserts the current script no
 longer exhibits them: (1) staging the wiki page into a fresh empty temp file
 with 'append-once' prepended a blank line to the top of the uploaded page
 ('overwrite' does not); (2) 'extract_url' returned only the last match, so
 the "more than one URL" ambiguity warning was dead -- it now emits every
 match; (3) an empty download-page scrape flowed into the local-file writes
 and corrupted them -- the script now fails fast on an empty 'latest' URL.
 .
 Each check runs old-broken (root cause reproduced) against new-fixed. The
 'dm-virtualbox-wiki-links-tests' command needs no root or network.

Package: systemcheck-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3
Description: Regression and hardening tests for systemcheck
 Static-analysis and functional test suite for Kicksecure/Whonix systemcheck.
 It reads the systemcheck shell fragments (from the installed package or, via
 SYSTEMCHECK_REPO, from a git checkout) and asserts the hardening and cleanup
 invariants: untrusted command/log output is HTML-neutralised before reaching
 the GUI setHtml() path (the log-checker sanitize-before-br_add ordering),
 result lines use the shared green $status_ok token, menu breadcrumbs are pure
 ASCII, ${output_opts[@]} is always quoted, and the parse_cmd short options are
 unambiguous. It also runs the pure bash helpers (leaprun_cmd_describe,
 remediation_instructions) in isolation and checks their session-aware output.
 Needs neither root, privleap, a Tor daemon, nor an X server. The suite targets
 the installed systemcheck by default; set SYSTEMCHECK_REPO to a checkout to
 test that instead.

Package: tor-control-panel-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 python3-pyqt5,
 tor-control-panel
Description: Regression and feature tests for tor-control-panel
 Headless test suite for tor-control-panel (which now also contains the merged
 anon-connection-wizard). It drives the real torrc_gen / tor_status logic and
 the PyQt5 AnonConnectionWizard / TorControlPanel widgets under the Qt offscreen
 platform plugin, with the torrc paths redirected to a temp directory and the
 privileged 'leaprun' helpers stubbed, so it needs neither root, privleap, a Tor
 daemon, nor an X server.
 .
 Feature coverage ('tor-control-panel-tests' command): torrc generation and
 parse round-trip for every Bridges type (None, obfs4, snowflake, meek, custom
 bridges) and Proxy type (None, SOCKS4, SOCKS5, with and without
 authentication).
 .
 Regression coverage of the bugs from arraybolt3's review and test plan (Whonix
 forum thread "Tor controller GUI"): custom bridges silently replaced by default
 obfs4 bridges on reconfigure (a '# Custom bridges are used' marker typo in
 parse_torrc); the anon-connection-wizard crash on Cancel (an uninitialised
 bootstrap_thread attribute); and duplicate 'Disable network' / 'Enable network'
 entries in the bridges selector (a hard-coded combo index). The interactive GUI
 walkthrough from the same test plan is shipped as skipped tests. The suite
 targets the installed tor-control-panel by default; set TCP_REPO to a checkout
 to test that instead.

Package: msgcollector-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 bash (>= 4),
 python3
Description: Fuzz tests for msgcollector CLI message rendering
 Randomized in-process fuzzer for msgcollector's --messagecli rendering bash,
 which rewrites an HTML message for the terminal over attacker-influenceable
 content (systemcheck feeds it journal lines, Tor control output, package
 names). It targets cli_links_to_footnotes -- the <a href> to footnote rewriter
 -- and asserts it never hangs, never crashes, consumes every well-formed
 anchor, and keeps a consistent footnote/URL list on adversarial input
 (crafted nested anchors, hrefs containing tags, control bytes). It reads the
 msgcollector script from the installed package or, via MSGCOLLECTOR_REPO, from
 a git checkout. Needs neither root, privleap, nor an X server.

Package: web-analyzer-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 nodejs
Description: Comprehensive test for the output-lies web text analyzer
 analyzer.js is the client-side, DOM-free classifier behind the output-lies
 Analyze page (output-lies.github.io). It flags every codepoint that is not
 plain printable ASCII (bidi controls, zero-width and invisible-format
 characters, deceptive whitespace, homoglyph-prone scripts, C0/C1 control bytes,
 line/paragraph separators, combining marks, variation selectors, tag characters
 and private use) and names the class of each. Because the module is pure, this
 suite drives it directly under node, with no browser.
 .
 It asserts the class of every boundary codepoint (each range edge and the
 codepoint just outside it), so a fenceposted range is caught; the known
 real-world traps; astral-plane safety (an emoji is one codepoint); the analyze()
 token splitting, where safe runs coalesce and the item list reconstructs the
 input exactly; toAscii() stripping; and hex() formatting. No root, no network.
 It resolves analyzer.js from OUTPUT_LIES_REPO (an output-lies.github.io
 checkout) and SKIPs (exit 77) when the module is absent.

Package: secure-terminal-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3
Description: Tests for the secure-terminal sanitization core
 secure_terminal.sanitize is the pure, Qt-free core behind the secure-terminal
 emulator (secure-terminal.github.io): it decides what child output is safe to
 display and classifies anything that is not. Because it has no GUI dependency,
 this suite drives it directly under python3 with no PyQt6.
 .
 It exercises render_output() across the strip / show / reveal display modes
 (non-ASCII to underscore, legitimate unicode rendered while invisible/bidi/format
 classes stay neutralized, and <U+XXXX> reveal), escape stripping, the paste
 sanitizer and its unicode/control classification, the safe-colour SGR parser
 with its black-on-black contrast guard, and the NO_COLOR / TERM=dumb handling. It
 also statically asserts the widget layer never routes output into an HTML sink.
 It resolves the module from SECURE_TERMINAL_REPO (a secure-terminal checkout)
 and SKIPs (exit 77) when absent. No root, no network.

Package: dist-ai-tests-all
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 bash (>= 4)
Description: Aggregate runner for the dist-ai test suites
 Runs the dist-ai regression, fuzz, e2e, and integration suites in one pass,
 aggregates the per-suite result (PASS / FAIL / SKIP / TIMEOUT), and exits
 non-zero if any suite failed. Categories are selected with --core / --fuzz /
 --e2e / --integration / --all (default: --core).
 .
 With --repo-root DIR every suite is pointed at a derivative-maker checkout so
 the in-tree code is tested rather than the installed package; without it each
 suite falls back to its installed or auto-detected target and reports SKIP
 when the target is absent. The individual test packages are Recommends, not
 Depends, so this runner can be installed alongside any subset of them.
Recommends: check-ref-commits-for-unicode-tests,
 dm-virtualbox-wiki-links-tests,
 genmkfile-tests,
 git-meld-tests,
 grep-find-unicode-wrapper-tests,
 msgcollector-tests,
 onion-grater-tests,
 open-link-confirmation-tests,
 privleap-tests,
 sanitize-string-tests,
 secure-terminal-tests,
 sdwdate-gui-tests,
 stcat-family-tests,
 stdisplay-tests,
 systemcheck-tests,
 tor-control-panel-tests,
